{
  "doc_id": "17585",
  "text": "The accumulation and aggregation of A␤ is a key event in the pathogenesis of AD, and preventing the formation or disrupting A␤ aggregation, thereby reducing neuronal dysfunction in the brain has been proposed as a therapeutic strategy. Inhibitors and modulators of A␤ aggregation, including peptide, protein and small molecular classes of natural and synthetic origin, have been shown to modulate toxicity of A␤ in vitro and in vivo [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Latrepirdine is a small polycyclic molecule belonging to a class of pro-neurogenic compounds [CITATION_3] . Findings from previous studies suggest that the ability of latrepirdine to modulate protein aggregation may explain its action in promoting the clearance of protein aggregates and could contribute to its neuroprotective mechanism of action [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . This study has addressed whether latrepirdine alters A␤ oligomer formation and if these effects were related to the amelioration of A␤ neurotoxicity in vitro.",
